crops.presented_by: Mr. R. T. Baker, curator, Technological Museum
crops.description: Seeds. Quoted notes taken from Baker and Smith, Eucalypts and Their Essential Oils (1902). A tall, quick-growing tree, sometimes attaining a height of 150 feet and a diameter of 2 to 5 feet. Bark on old trees deeply furrowed and dark gray to blackish up to the branches. It is famous for its eucalyptol oil. Distribution: Often 200 feet tall, found on steep mountain slopes in the southeastern part of New South Wales, Australia. See Baker and Smith for further description.

crops.presented_by: Mr. R. T. Baker, curator, Technological Museum
crops.description: Seeds. Quoted notes taken from Baker and Smith, Eucalypts and Their Essential Oils (1902). A tall, foliaceous tree, sometimes attaining 100 feet, with a dark-colored, stringy bark. Timber pale-colored, darker than White-mahogany (Eucalyptus acmenoides Schau.). It is subject to attack by a borer which deteriorates its quality as a marketable timber. The wood is hard and close-grained but rather inferior to White-mahogany, a fact well known to timber-getters. Distribution: Sometimes 100 feet tall, found in the northern part of New South Wales, Australia. See Baker and Smith for further description.

crops.presented_by: Mr. C. L. Legat, Chief Conservator of Forests, Forest Department
crops.description: A shrub or tree from 6 to 40 feet high or more. Wood much thought of by the natives; white and compact, or black in the center like ebony, and useful for many purposes. Fruit 1/2 to 1 inch in diameter, edible. Range extends from Abyssinia and Mozambique on the east to Angola, the Kongo, and the Gold Coast on the west; apparently very widely scattered. Known as monkey guava in the west and as aje in Abyssinia. (Hiern, Ebenaceae, pp. 165–166.)
Cuttings. Variety: Lombard. Black with reddish interior. Quoted notes by Mr. Pantelides.
Cuttings. Variety: Vassilica (Royal). Black. Quoted notes by Mr. Pantelides.
Cuttings. Variety: Ysterounelea. Bears fruit twice a year; fruits are very small but very sweet. Quoted notes by Mr. Pantelides.
Cuttings. Variety: Ambourcouna. Black; fruits twice a year. Quoted notes by Mr. Pantelides.
Cuttings. Variety: Metilinia. White; these succeed also among oranges. Quoted notes by Mr. Pantelides.
Cuttings. Variety: Apatsiana. Black; table variety. Quoted notes by Mr. Pantelides.
Cuttings. Variety: Crassera. Black wine grapes noted for their great production. Quoted notes by Mr. Pantelides.

Cuttings. Variety: Arcoussia. Rose-colored wine and table grapes. From these grapes was made the ancient wine of Chios. This vine is long lived and succeeds as a climber; it may cover a pavilion of about 100 square meters (approximately 120 square yards) and may yield up to a ton of fruit. Quoted notes by Mr. Pantelides.

crops.presented_by: Mr. O. W. Barrett, Chief, Division of Experiment Stations, Bureau of Agriculture
crops.institution_involved: Bureau of Agriculture (Division of Experiment Stations); Bureau of Plant Industry
crops.description: Presented through Mr. Lyster H. Dewey, Bureau of Plant Industry. Manila maguey is cultivated in the Philippines and to a limited extent in India, where it produces the fiber known as Bombay aloe. It is cultivated on a large scale in Java, producing a very excellent quality of fiber that has been marketed under the misleading name 'Java sisal'; Javanese growers propose the name 'cantala' for this fiber. The plant grows well in Java on rich, loamy soils where heavy rainfall and lack of lime make sisal or henequen cultivation impracticable. This plant would probably grow well in the eastern part of Porto Rico. (Dewey.)

crops.description: Collected at Nuwara Eliya. Collection No. 85, dated August 27, 1911. A spiny-stemmed red raspberry with small, smooth fruits borne in clusters. Flowers white. Stems ascending 4 to 10 feet. (Piper.)
